<p>
    <strong>Look at the Sound</strong>
</p>
<p>
    <em>
        "Artistic man can be wholly satisfied only by the unification of all forms of art in the service of the common artistic endeavor. Any fragmentation of
        his artistic sensibilities limits his freedom, prevents him from becoming fully what he is capable of being… When eye and ear mutually reinforce the
        impressions each receives, only then artistic man present in all his fullness. "
    </em>
</p>
<p>
    <em></em>
</p>
<p>
    <em>Richard Wagner, The Artwork Of The Future (1850)</em>
</p>
<p>
    <strong>How does image work as an agent of meaning in a performance of music?</strong>
</p>
<p>
    The purpose of this research is to analyze and explore a meaningful ways of images complimenting sound. In fact I have been considering collaboration with
    a Sonology Master postgraduate who as a matter of fact confronted me with his struggle to attract and expand his audience.
</p>
<p>
    In order to find a way to visualize any sounds I am doing a study on intuitive reactions and co-operation of the senses while listening to the music or
    sounds. Furthermore I am analyzing how audiovisual art disciplines as abstract film, computer graphics and graphic sound progressed through out the time.
</p>
<p>
    In addition to this I have been researching neurological phenomenon of Chromesthesia.
</p>
<p>
    The anticipated outcome of this research is to explore ways of visualizing music in graphical way that is based on scientific theories and yet remains to
    be emotional.
</p>
<br clear="all"/>
<p>
    <strong>Introduction</strong>
</p>
<p>
    This report examines beneficial ways of visualizing sound performance from graphic designer and sonologist point of view. Based on my research of
</p>
<p>
    a historical narrative of audio visual arts and phenomenon of Chromosthesia –
</p>
<p>
    I am trying to find a way that we actually can look at the sound during the performance.
</p>
<p>
    I strongly believe that we should cherish the emotional on symbolic connection between the music and visual arts. But even so there is a hypothesis about
    something more than just an abstract connection between our senses of hearing and seeing. Eventually I came across actual "wonder"
</p>
<p>
    in which heard sounds automatically and involuntary evoke an experience of
</p>
<p>
    a color. However, until relatively recently, little had been written on this form of synesthesia<em>*. </em>A particular problem area of my research
    question is to analyze already exciting forms of audiovisual arts. Overall there are endless possibilities to visualize sound or music. In this report you
    will find examples that are explicitly related to field of the sonology or graphic design.
</p>
<p>
    Based on available literature research, interviews and experiment this report will examine possibilities how does image works as an agent of meaning in
    musical performance.
</p>
<p>
    <em>
        * Oxford dictionary. Physiology &amp; Psychology - The production of a sense impression relating to one sense or part of the body by stimulation of
        another sense or part of the body.
    </em>
</p>
<em>
    <br clear="all"/>
</em>
<p>
    <strong>Previous experience with visualizing music was a trigger to start this research.</strong>
</p>
<p>
    <strong></strong>
</p>
<p>
    Recently I had a fruitful and trilling collaborating with a alumna student from Royal Conservatory The Hague. First Nerea Vera approached me and proposed
    me to introduce some graphic design in one of her percussion pieces by Iannis Xenakis - Psappha. After the first meeting she made it clear - that a
    majority of concerts of well-known pieces have really dull atmosphere. She believed that graphic design or some visuals really could make a change and
    lighten up the space. We agreed to create visual piece that would represent her music style and characteristics of Iannis Xenakis composition. As a final
    result I created an animation that was built the way as this peace was composed. My visualizations were inspired by dynamic rhythm, mathematical
    composition structure and muscularity of the piece.
</p>
<p>
    I did enjoy this cross "field" working method. However I believe that one discipline can learn from the other a lot. It is possible to have surprising
    results by learning principles from other fields and applying them in territories that concerns my field of expertise. As a matter of fact I believe that
    my mission as graphic designer is to help my clients to stand out and be seen. And there is no other discipline that deserves this more than musicians and
    composers.
</p>
<p>
    Siamak Anvari approached me with his request and interest in collaboration with me. His request was similar as I described before in case of Nerea.
</p>
<p>
    Siamak is alumni of master program of "Sinology department" of Royal Conservatory The Hague. Also he faces the same struggle as Nerea. It is hard to
    attract visitors and fill up the audience since the dull atmosphere of events. It really lacks some other dimension and added value.
</p>
<br clear="all"/>
<p>
    <strong>Premise</strong>
</p>
<p>
    <strong></strong>
</p>
<p>
    People who are musically trained listens to music vary different way than non-trained listeners. They tend to turn their attention more on textures and
    melody before other aspects of musical piece. Since I am not musically trained and have no special talents regarding the field of music; I have to keep in
    mind that I do approach compositions different way than musically trained person.
</p>
<p>
    Due that my research does not go in to the depth of the professional music listening or production.
</p>
<p>
    However good hearing does not necessarily insure skilled listening, conversely, poor hearing does not indicate an inability to listen to music. It is
    something to keep in mind before approaching any auditory. Musical visualization can support ability to listen music by evoking sound trough a sight.
    Nevertheless there are also shortcomings of multi - sensory method of listening to music, though that was discussed with music professionals. As an example
    it is possible that visuals can change a meaning of musical peace and distract listeners attention from musical piece.
</p>
